AgriBank, Cheung Kong, Jiangxi Copper: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-03-30T00:54:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/agribank-cheung-kong-jiangxi-copper-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  was little changed at 23,060.36. The
Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, rose 0.2 percent to 12,920.44.  Agricultural Bank of China Ltd. (1288)  (1288 HK): The nation’s
fourth-largest lender by market value said 2010 profit grew 46
percent to 94.87 billion yuan ($14.5 billion), exceeding the
91.1 billion yuan average estimate of 17 analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg News. The stock declined 1.9 percent to HK$4.13.  Air China Ltd. (601111)  (753 HK): The nation’s largest international
carrier more than doubled profit to 12 billion yuan last year.
The average estimate of 15 analysts compiled by Bloomberg was
11.5 billion yuan. The stock fell 0.6 percent to HK$7.16.  Angang Steel Co. (347 HK): China’s biggest Hong Kong-traded
steelmaker incurred a net loss of 720 million yuan in the six
months ended Dec. 31, compared with a profit of 2.3 billion yuan
a year earlier. The numbers were derived by deducting six-month
figures from full-year profit released on the Shenzhen stock
exchange under international accounting standards. The stock
slid 0.2 percent to HK$10.14.  Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd. (293)  (293 HK):  Asia ’s second-biggest
listed carrier by sales suspended some Japan flights for two
weeks from April 1 to April 15 because of weakening demand, it
said in an e-mailed statement. The airline expects “several
months of weakness with a recovery toward the summer” for
Japanese air travel demand, according to the statement. The
stock fell 0.1 percent to HK$18.34.  China Cosco Holdings Co. (1919 HK): Asia’s largest shipping
company by market value said full-year net income was 6.86
billion yuan last year, against a net loss of 7.47 billion a
year earlier. The average forecast of 14 analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg was 6.77 billion yuan. The stock increased 0.3 percent
to HK$8.09.  China Southern Airlines Co. (1055 HK): The nation’s largest
carrier plans to expand its fleet to 461 planes this year from
422 in 2010. The airline will get its first Airbus SAS A380 in
August and the company may add to its fleet of Boeing Co. 777
freighters, President and Chief Executive Officer Tan Wan Geng
said. The stock fell 4 percent to HK$3.38.  China Unicom (Hong Kong) Ltd. (762 HK): The nation’s
second-largest mobile phone company said full-year profit fell
to 3.85 billion yuan ($587 million) from 9.56 billion yuan a
year earlier. The stock advanced 0.2 percent to HK$13.10.  China Yurun Food Group Ltd. (1068)  (1068 HK): The meat supplier
said full-year net income jumped 56 percent to HK$2.73 billion
($350 million) from a year earlier. The average estimate of 15
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg was HK$2.48 billion. The stock
declined 0.6 percent to HK$23.65.  Cheung Kong  (Holdings) Ltd. (1 HK): Hong Kong’s No. 2
developer by market value said full-year net income rose 35
percent to HK$26.5 billion from a year earlier. That compares
with the average HK$20.2 billion of 12 analysts’ estimates
compiled by Bloomberg. The stock gained 0.5 percent to HK$122.50.  CSR Corp. (1766 HK): China’s biggest train maker said net
income rose 51 percent last year to 2.5 billion yuan from a year
earlier. The average estimate of eight analysts compiled by
Bloomberg was 2.8 billion yuan. The stock dropped 1 percent to
HK$8.04.  Huaneng Power International Inc. (902)  (902 HK): The unit of
China’s biggest power producer said full-year net profit fell 32
percent to 3.35 billion yuan from a year earlier. The average
profit forecast of 16 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg was 4.07
billion yuan. The stock retreated 0.2 percent to HK$4.51.  Hutchison Whampoa Ltd. (13)  (13 HK): Billionaire Li Ka-shing’s
biggest company said its full-year profit rose 47 percent to
HK$20 billion from a year earlier, exceeding the HK$16.4 billion
average of nine analysts’ estimates compiled by Bloomberg. The
stock declined 2.1 percent to HK$88.80.  Jiangxi Copper Co. (358 HK): China’s biggest producer of
the metal said net income rose to 2.79 billion yuan in the six
months ended Dec. 31 from 1.11 billion yuan a year earlier. The
result was derived by deducting the six-month figures from full-
year profit released on the Shanghai stock exchange, based on
international accounting standards. The stock was unchanged at
HK$24.65.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. (2318 HK):  China ’s second-
largest insurer said profit climbed 25 percent to 17.3 billion
yuan, compared with a 16.9 billion yuan average estimate of 12
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News. The stock decreased 1.4
percent to HK$75.05.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Tokyo  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
